# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arsik
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arsik/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:arsik/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:arsik/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:arsik/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:arsik/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:arsik/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:arsik/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:arsik/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:arsik/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:arsik/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:arsik/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:arsik/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:arsik/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:arsik/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:arsik/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:arsik/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:arsik/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:arsik/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:arsik/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:arsik/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:arsik/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:arsik/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:arsik/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:arsik/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:arsik/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:arsik/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:arsik/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:arsik/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:arsik/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:arsik/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:arsik/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:arsik/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:arsik/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:arsik/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:arsik/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:arsik/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:arsik/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:arsik/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:arsik/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:arsik/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:arsik/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:arsik/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:arsik/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:arsik/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:arsik/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:arsik/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:arsik/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:arsik/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:arsik/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:arsik/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:arsik/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:arsik/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:arsik/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:arsik/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:arsik/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:arsik/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:arsik/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:arsik/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:arsik/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:arsik/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:arsik/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:arsik/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:arsik/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:arsik/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:arsik/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:arsik/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:arsik/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:arsik/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:arsik/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:arsik/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:arsik/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:arsik/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:arsik/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:arsik/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:arsik/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:arsik/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:arsik/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:arsik/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:arsik/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:arsik/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:arsik/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:arsik/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:arsik/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:arsik/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:arsik/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:arsik/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:arsik/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:arsik/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:arsik/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:arsik/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:arsik/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:arsik/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:arsik/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:arsik/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:arsik/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:arsik/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:arsik/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:arsik/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:arsik/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:arsik/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:arsik/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:arsik/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:arsik/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:arsik/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:arsik/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:arsik/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:arsik/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:arsik/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:arsik/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Currently, there are no alcohol bans being enforced in Indonesia, with the exception of Aceh.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since 2014, anyone found consuming alcohol or breaching the codes on moral conduct, whether residents or visitors to Aceh, could face between six and nine cane lashes.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In other parts of Indonesia, to appease the Islamic parties and pressure groups, the government agreed to apply mild restriction measures on alcohol, which includes high taxation and limited bans.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia is among the countries that apply high taxes on imported alcoholic beverages; in 2015, import tax on alcohol jumped to 150%.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in 2015, the Indonesian government banned the sale of alcohol from minimarkets and small shops, with the exception of Bali province, though sale was allowed in supermarkets, restaurants, bars, clubs and hotels.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, in more cosmopolitan Indonesian cities like Jakarta, Medan and Surabaya, and also in tourism hotspots such as Bali, Yogyakarta and Batam, alcoholic beverages are readily available, yet with higher prices, owing to the high tax applied upon alcoholic beverages.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2016, Indonesian Malt Beverage Producers Association (GIMMI) called the House of Representatives to draft for comprehensive regulations on the chain of production and the marketing of alcoholic beverages, instead of total prohibition.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since ancient times, local alcoholic beverages were developed by natives in the archipelago.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some panels in 9th century Borobudur bas-reliefs depicted drink vendors, *warung* (small restaurant), and there is a panel depicting a building with people drinking (possibly alcoholic beverages), dancing and having fun, seeming to depict a tavern or lodging house.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to a Chinese source, Yingya Shenglan (c.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] 15th century) the people of Java in Majapahit kingdom drank wine made from palm sap called *tuak* (palm wine).
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, by the 16th century Islam began to supplant Hinduism and Buddhism as the major religion in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Since then, as a Muslim-majority country, Indonesian Muslims share Islamic dietary laws that prohibit alcoholic beverages.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Nevertheless, the local alcohol-drinking culture still survives, at least among less-religious members of society and among the non-Muslim community.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Certain ethno-cultural regions which are predominantly Christian are known for their affinity to alcohol-drinking traditions; such as the Batak, Torajan, Minahasan, Ambonese and Papuan.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia has its own traditional alcoholic beverages prepared by fermenting rice grain, gluten, sugar palm sap, and coconuts.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] According to culinary expert William Wongso, the culture of drinking distilled alcohol was never strong in Indonesia, with only a few regions having developed it.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Batak community in North Sumatra, *tuak* (palm liquor) is a compulsory drink in the celebrations and became a tradition in the community.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Batak tribes are predominantly of Christian Protestant faith, yet some of its clans are Muslim.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] A traditional Batak bar serving *tuak* is called a *lapo tuak*.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Toraja lands of South Sulawesi, their version of *tuak* — made from fermented sugar palm sap, is called *ballo*.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Torajan traditional ceremonies, rituals and celebrations, *ballo* is always served, either as a prerequisite for the ritual; as an offering for ancestral spirits, as well as for drinks for guests.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Ballo* is also commonly consumed by the neighboring Bugis ethnic group.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In the Minahasa region of North Sulawesi, an almost identical palm liquor, also made from sugar palm sap, is called *saguer*.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Nusa Tenggara and Maluku Islands the people also drink palm wine, locally known as *sopi*.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Also in the Minahasa region, the people drink a highly alcoholic drink called *cap tikus* (lit.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Cap tikus* is made from distilled *saguer* or *sopi* (palm wine), which increases its alcohol content.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The origin of *cap tikus* brand is unclear.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is suggested that circa 1820s, prior to the 1830 Java War, the KNIL Minahasan legion found and bought distilled *saguer* or *sopi* sold in blue bottles embossed with the image of mouse sold by a Chinese merchant in Fort Amsterdam in Manado.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Today however, because of poor regulation on alcohol production in this region, this traditional home-made *cap tikus* industry is considered as an illegal beverage, due to the high prevalence of mortal alcohol poisoning.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bottled *brem bali* (Balinese rice wine) and *arrack* are popular beverages in the Hindu-majority island of Bali.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem* is a brownish colored liquor with 5% alcohol.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] For Balinese people it has a religious significance too.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] *Brem*, *arak* and *tuak* are required for *tabuhan* (offerings) to the gods.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In Solo, Central Java, *ciu*, a local adaptation of Chinese wine, made from cider molasses of sugarcane is well known.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] It is linked to Solo's history as a sugar plantation and production center in colonial times.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Dutch Colonial state was established in Indonesia in the 1800s.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The colonial Dutch brought their European drinking culture to the East Indies, most prominently with beer.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The Heineken beer company established its brewery factory in Surabaya in 1929 during the Dutch colonial rule of Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] By the 1960s, Indonesians developed their own local brands of beer, which included Bintang Beer (nationalized from Heineken) and Anker Beer.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In April 2019, the East Nusa Tenggara provincial government supported the legal aspect of production and distribution of sopi, a local traditional alcoholic beverage.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] This policy is very likely to make sopi the first fully supported alcoholic product by the local government in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] A Presidential regulation signed by Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono in 2013 gave legal cover to distribution of alcohol, it classified alcoholic beverages in Indonesia in three categories.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Drinks having an alcohol percentage less than 5% (A class), 5%–20% (B class) and more than 20% (C class).
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] It was replacement of the 1997 decree after the Supreme Court abolished it following appeals from hard-line religious groups like the Islamic Defenders Front.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The 2012 court ruling came after a draft bill proposed by the United Development Party (PPP) to completely ban the sale, production and consumption of alcohol in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] However, the 2013 presidential regulation was welcomed by travel agencies in the wake of the harmful effects of the proposed draft on tourism.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Prices of wine and spirits in Indonesia increased by 140.5% and 154.4% respectively between 2009 and 2014.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2015 the government further hiked the import tariff on wine and spirits which nearly doubled the price of alcoholic beverages.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Some foreign companies which sell alcohol in Indonesia are Diageo, Pernod Ricard, Remy Cointreau and Bacardi.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] PT Multi Bintang is the largest domestic brewery of Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] As per market experts, because of various regulations, alcohol sales are declining in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Bintang Beer of Multi Bintang brewery is the largest selling beer of Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Multi Bintang is a subsidiary of Heineken Asia Pacific.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2011, Bintang Beer won the Gold Medal for the Lager Beer Category and was awarded 'Champion Beer 2011' at the world's class beer competition, the Brewing Industry International Award (BIIA 2011) in London.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In 2014 Bintang Radler was introduced which was the first flavored beer produced domestically in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other major beer producers are Delta Djakarta known for its Anker Beer, and PT Bali Hai Brewery Indonesia known for its Bali Hai.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Indonesia also produces other brands, including San Miguel Beer and Asahi beer, under license.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Diageo manufactures Smirnoff and Captain Morgan products in Bali, which qualifies both brands for classification as locally produced spirits.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The high prices of alcohol beverages in Indonesia, caused by high taxation and restrictions, has led to cases of illegal alcohol in the country.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] As the legal and imported alcoholic beverages become unaffordable, locals turn to illegal bootlegged alcohol for a cheaper drink.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illegal alcoholic drinks are known in Indonesian as *alkohol oplosan* (lit.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] "solved alcohol") and account for over 80% of the alcohol consumed in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] These illicitly produced liquors which are traditionally home-made, are considered illegal by Indonesian law, due to the high incidence of deadly alcohol poisoning.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] The *lapen* liquor from Yogyakarta for example, is made from industrial alcohol of 85% volume mixed with water with a 1:4 or 5 alcohol to water ratio; then mixed with fruit essence as a flavoring agent.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In February 2010, 16 people died and 5 *lapen* sellers were arrested in Yogyakarta, due to alcohol poisoning and illicit alcohol production.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] In September 2010, three Russian Sukhoi fighter technicians died in Makassar from methanol poisoning in their drinks.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Yogyakarta residents were again affected by badly made alcohol in 2016.
[src:arsik/alcohol-in-indonesia] Other traditionally made alcoholic spirits such as Solo's *ciu*, Manado's *cap tikus*, and some Balinese *arrack* are known as illegal alcohol, also due to the high incidence of alcohol poisoning.
[src:arsik/amplang] The shape and size of amplang might vary, from traditional elongated "tiger nails" to dice or ping-pong balls.
[src:arsik/amplang] The colour may range from yellow to light brown.
[src:arsik/amplang] In Indonesia, amplang is traditionally associated with Samarinda, the capital city of East Kalimantan, since the amplang cracker home industry has thrived in the city since the 1970s.
[src:arsik/amplang] Traditionally, amplang was made from *ikan pipih* or *ikan belida* (*Chitala lopis*).
[src:arsik/amplang] However, since this freshwater fish had become scarce, amplang makers replaced them with *ikan tenggiri* (wahoo) or *gabus* (striped snakehead).
[src:arsik/amplang] From Samarinda, the popularity of this savoury fish cracker spread to other cities in the Borneo island, such as Balikpapan, Banjarmasin, Pontianak, and even to Sabah in Malaysia.
[src:arsik/amplang] Amplang is often sought as *oleh-oleh* (foodstuff gift or souvenir) by those who visited East Kalimantan.
[src:arsik/amplang] Today, amplang made by home industries in Kalimantan has been widely distributed, available in marketplaces and supermarkets in Indonesian cities, such as Jakarta, Bandung, Surabaya, and Medan.
[src:arsik/amplang] Amplang is commonly produced by home industries in Samarinda, East Kalimantan in Indonesia.
[src:arsik/amplang] Other than Samarinda, amplang production centres also can be found in Balikpapan, Pontianak in West Kalimantan and Banjarmasin in South Kalimantan.
[src:arsik/amplang] In neighbouring Malaysia, amplang is mainly produced on the east coast of Sabah, particularly in the town of Tawau.
[src:arsik/amplang] Today, the makers of amplang in East Kalimantan produce the snack not only with a fish flavor, but in a variety of flavors such as crab and seaweed.
[src:arsik/amplang] Nevertheless, the original amplang kuku macan remains the most popular.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Angeun Lada is a soup dish with a spicy and savory taste, as well as rich in spices.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Its broth tends to be thick and reddish in color due to the use of chili peppers.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Fat and small diced pieces of meat can be seen floating in the broth.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] One of the main distinctive features that sets Angeun Lada apart from other soup dishes is the use of culantro, also known as *Walangan*.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] These leaves have a very strong aroma, similar to that of a rice ear bug insect, and provide a unique and refreshing flavor.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Although the aroma may seem unusual for those tasting it for the first time, the scent and taste of *walang* are not overpowering when eaten with meat.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Culantro is commonly found in the southern regions of Banten and contains essential oils.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] The Baduy even use culantro as a natural pesticide to repel rice pests by burning it in their field huts.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] The main ingredients of Angeun Lada vary, but it generally uses beef tripe, buffalo meat, beef, or goat meat.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] In addition, it can also be mixed with vegetables.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Angeun Lada is usually served as a side dish with rice or *ketupat*.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Angeun Lada can be consumed for breakfast, lunch, or dinner.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Currently, Angeun Lada is rarely sold and can only be found at food stalls in certain areas around Lebak, Serang, Pandeglang, and Rangkasbitung.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] A popular place to taste Angeun Lada in Pandeglang is *Warung Cep Udin* at Sukarela Field, Pandeglang.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] In addition, extensive publications are being carried out to raise public awareness about Angeun Lada.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] Community participation is also considered very important for its preservation, such as by continuing to cook it, serve it to guests, or sell it.
[src:arsik/angeun-lada] The Cultural Preservation Center Region VIII also organizes Angeun Lada cooking competitions, such as during the Surosowan Cultural Festival.
[src:arsik/anise] The flavor and aroma of its seeds have similarities with some other spices and herbs, such as star anise, fennel, liquorice, and tarragon.
[src:arsik/anise] It is widely cultivated and used to flavor food, candy, and alcoholic drinks, especially around the Mediterranean.
[src:arsik/anise] The name "anise" is derived via Old French from the Latin words *anīsum* or *anēthum* from Greek ἄνηθον *ánēthon* referring to dill.
[src:arsik/anise] An obsolete English word for anise is *anet*, also coming from *ănēthum*.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise is an herbaceous annual plant growing to 60–90 centimetres (2–3 feet) or more.
[src:arsik/anise] The leaves at the base of the plant are simple, 1–5 cm (3⁄8–2 inches) long and shallowly lobed, while leaves higher on the stems are feathery or lacy, pinnate, divided into numerous small leaflets.
[src:arsik/anise] Both leaves and flowers are produced in large, loose clusters.
[src:arsik/anise] The flowers are either white or yellow, approximately 3 millimetres (1⁄8 in) in diameter, produced in dense umbels.
[src:arsik/anise] The fruit is a dry oblong and curved schizocarp, 4–6 mm (1⁄6–1⁄4 in) long, usually called "aniseed".
[src:arsik/anise] Anise is a food plant for the larvae of some Lepidoptera species (butterflies and moths), including the lime-speck pug and wormwood pug.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise was first cultivated in the Middle East, and was brought to Europe for its medicinal value.
[src:arsik/anise] It has been cultivated in Egypt for approximately 4,000 years.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise plants grow best in light, fertile, well-drained soil.
[src:arsik/anise] The seeds should be planted as soon as the ground warms up in spring.
[src:arsik/anise] Because the plants have a taproot, they do not transplant well after being established so they should either be started in their final location or be transplanted while the seedlings are still small.
[src:arsik/anise] Western cuisines have long used anise to flavor dishes, drinks, and candies.
[src:arsik/anise] The word is used for both the species of herb and its licorice-like flavor.
[src:arsik/anise] The most powerful flavor component of the essential oil of anise, anethole, is found in both anise and an unrelated spice indigenous to South China called star anise (*Illicium verum*) widely used in South Asian, Southeast Asian and East Asian dishes.
[src:arsik/anise] Star anise is considerably less expensive to produce and has gradually displaced *P. anisum* in Western markets.
[src:arsik/anise] While formerly produced in larger quantities, by 1999 world production of the essential oil of anise was 8 tons, compared to 400 tons of star anise.
[src:arsik/anise] As with all spices, the composition of anise varies considerably with origin and cultivation method.
[src:arsik/anise] These are typical values for the main constituents.
[src:arsik/anise] In particular, the anise seeds products should also contain more than 0.2 milliliter volatile oil per 100 grams of spice.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise is sweet and aromatic, distinguished by its characteristic flavor.
[src:arsik/anise] The culinary uses of anise are not limited only to sweets and confections, as it is a key ingredient in Mexican *atole de anís* and *champurrado*, which is similar to hot chocolate.
[src:arsik/anise] In India and Pakistan, it is taken as a digestive after meals, used in brines in the Italian region of Apulia and as a flavoring agent in Italian sausage, pepperoni and other Italian processed meat products.
[src:arsik/anise] The freshly chopped leaves are added to cheese spreads, dips or salads, while roots and stems impart a mild licorice flavor to soups and stews.
[src:arsik/anise] Outside the Mediterranean region, it is found in Colombian *aguardiente* and Mexican *Xtabentún*.
[src:arsik/anise] These liqueurs are clear, but on addition of water become cloudy, a phenomenon known as the ouzo effect or louche.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise is used together with other herbs and spices in some root beers, such as Virgil's in the United States.
[src:arsik/anise] According to Pliny the Elder, anise was used as a cure for sleeplessness, chewed with alexanders and a little honey in the morning to freshen the breath, and, when mixed with wine, as a remedy for asp bites (N.H.
[src:arsik/anise] In 19th-century medicine, anise was prepared as **aqua anisi** ("Water of Anise") in doses of an ounce or more and as **spiritus anisi** ("Spirit of Anise") in doses of 5–20 minims.
[src:arsik/anise] In Turkish folk medicine, its seeds have been used as an appetite stimulant, tranquilizer or diuretic.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise essential oil can be obtained from the fruits by either steam distillation or extraction using supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:arsik/anise] The yield of essential oil is influenced by the growing conditions and extraction process, with supercritical extraction being more efficient.
[src:arsik/anise] Regardless of the method of isolation the main component of the oil is anethole (80–90%), with minor components including 4-anisaldehyde, estragole and pseudoisoeugenyl-2-methylbutyrates amongst others.
[src:arsik/anise] 2008 to be 2–6% extracted oil by weight of raw seed material, 74–94% being *trans*-anethole and the remaining fraction estragole (methylchavicol), anisaldehyde and γ-himachalene.) Anethole is responsible for anise's characteristic odor and flavor.
[src:arsik/anise] Builders of steam locomotives in Britain incorporated capsules of aniseed oil into white metal plain bearings so the distinctive smell would give warning in case of overheating.
[src:arsik/anise] Anise can be made into a liquid scent and is used for both drag hunting and fishing.
[src:arsik/anise] It is put on fishing lures to attract fish.
[src:arsik/arsik] Distinctively Batak elements of the dish are the use of torch ginger fruit (*asam cikala*), and *andaliman* (similar to Sichuan pepper).
[src:arsik/arsik] Common Indonesian vegetables and spices such as shallots, garlic, ginger, fresh turmeric root and chili are also used.
[src:arsik/arsik] Andaliman, essential for the distinctive taste of the dish, is known to grow only in the Batak highlands of North Tapanuli and Samosir, hence this dish is regarded as being specifically of the Batak Toba and Mandailing people, who dwell in these areas.
[src:arsik/arsik] Besides gold fish or carp, saltwater fish such as rastrelliger (*kembung*) and snappers can also be used to make arsik.
[src:arsik/arsik] A meat variant of arsik also exists, with pork as the commonly cooked meat.
